---
import CodeBlock from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/CodeBlock.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import InlineCode from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/InlineCode.astro";
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="Nested Field Arrays"
	description="Nested field arrays with drag-and-drop reordering."
>
	<ContentSection label="What This Demonstrates">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Field arrays can be nested: each row in a top-level array can contain
			its own sub-array. This example shows a two-level structure where the
			outer array supports drag-and-drop reordering, and each outer row
			contains an inner array with its own insert/remove controls.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			The key detail: nested field arrays use a vector path (e.g.
			<InlineCode>[:field-array-1 idx :field-array-2]</InlineCode>) instead
			of a simple string name. Fork resolves this path into the correct
			location in the values map automatically.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Inner Field Array">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			The inner array component is straightforward. It receives the same
			namespaced handlers as any field array. The only difference is that
			it's mounted inside another field array's row:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`(defn field-array-2
  [{:keys [normalize-name]}
   {:fieldarray/keys [fields name insert remove
                      touched handle-change handle-blur]}]
  [:div {:style {:padding "1em"
                 :margin "0.5em"
                 :background "green"}}
   (doall
    (->> fields
         (map-indexed
          (fn [idx field]
            ^{:key (str name idx)}
            [:div
             [:input
              {:name (normalize-name :field-array-2/input)
               :value (get field :field-array-2/input)
               :on-change #(handle-change % idx)
               :on-blur #(handle-blur % idx)}]
             [:button
              {:type "button"
               :on-click #(remove idx)}
              "Remove"]
             (when (touched idx :field-array-2/input)
               [:p "I have been touched!"])]))))
   [:br]
   [:button
    {:type "button"
     :on-click #(insert {:field-array-2/input
                         (rand-nth [":)" ":D" "^_^" ":O"])})}
    "Add nested field array"]])`}
			language="clojure"
			filename="fieldarray.cljs"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Outer Field Array with Drag-and-Drop">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			The outer array uses drag-and-drop handlers and nests the inner array
			via <InlineCode>fork/field-array</InlineCode> with a vector path.
			The <InlineCode>drag-and-drop-handlers</InlineCode> function returns
			HTML5 drag attributes that you merge into each row's wrapper:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`(defn field-array-1
  [{:keys [normalize-name] :as props}
   {:fieldarray/keys [fields name insert remove
                      touched handle-change handle-blur
                      current-dragged-idx
                      next-droppable-target?
                      prev-droppable-target?
                      drag-and-drop-handlers]}]
  [:div
   (doall
    (->> fields
         (map-indexed
          (fn [idx field]
            ^{:key (str name idx)}
            [:div
             (merge
              (drag-and-drop-handlers :field-array-1 idx)
              {:style
               (cond-> {:padding "1em"
                        :margin "1em"
                        :background "blue"}
                 (= idx (current-dragged-idx :field-array-1))
                 (assoc :opacity 0.5)
                 (next-droppable-target? :field-array-1 idx)
                 (assoc :border-bottom "10px solid black")
                 (prev-droppable-target? :field-array-1 idx)
                 (assoc :border-top "10px solid black"))})
             [:div "DRAG ME!"]
             [:br]
             [:input
              {:name (normalize-name :field-array-1/input)
               :value (get field :field-array-1/input)
               :on-change #(handle-change % idx)
               :on-blur #(handle-blur % idx)}]
             (when (touched idx :field-array-1/input)
               [:p "I have been touched!"])
             [:br]
             ;; Nested field array with vector path
             [fork/field-array
              {:props props
               :name [:field-array-1 idx :field-array-2]}
              field-array-2]
             [:br]
             [:button
              {:type "button"
               :on-click #(remove idx)}
              "Remove"]]))))
   [:button
    {:type "button"
     :on-click #(insert
                 {:field-array-1/input "new input!"
                  :field-array-2
                  [{:field-array-2/input "new input nested!"}]})}
    "Add field array"]])`}
			language="clojure"
			filename="fieldarray.cljs"
		/>
		<Callout type="info" title="Vector paths">
			The nested field array's <InlineCode>:name</InlineCode> is
			<InlineCode>[:field-array-1 idx :field-array-2]</InlineCode>. Fork
			resolves this to the correct position in the values map:
			<InlineCode>(get-in values [:field-array-1 idx :field-array-2])</InlineCode>.
			This works at any nesting depth.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Parent Form">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			The parent form initializes the nested data structure and passes
			an external <InlineCode>:state</InlineCode> ratom so you can
			inspect the full form state alongside the UI:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`(defn view []
  (r/with-let [state (r/atom nil)]
    [fork/form
     {:state state
      :keywordize-keys true
      :initial-values
      {:field-array-1
       [{:field-array-1/input "hello1"
         :field-array-2
         [{:field-array-2/input "hello nested1"}]}
        {:field-array-1/input "hello2"
         :field-array-2
         [{:field-array-2/input "hello nested2"}]}
        {:field-array-1/input "hello3"
         :field-array-2
         [{:field-array-2/input "hello nested3"}]}]}}
     (fn [props]
       [:form.manage-pages
        [fork/field-array
         {:props props
          :name :field-array-1}
         field-array-1]
        [:br]
        [:pre (with-out-str
                (pprint/pprint @(:state props)))]])]))`}
			language="clojure"
			filename="fieldarray.cljs"
		/>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
